A portion of the W6 Lot will be closed for staging vehicles, and Fields 10-12 will be closed for landing helicopters: Seattle Parks and Recreation, Seattle Fire Department, the Washington National Guard and Northwest Regional Aviation will conduct a joint helicopter and communications exercise on Wednesday, March 30, noon to 5 p.m.. The goal of the exercise is to better prepare the city of Seattle and first responders in the event of a major disaster that displaces a large portion of the population, and requires search and rescue operations, transport of supplies, and transport of injured victims. The exercise is part of a statewide preparedness exercise organized by Northwest Regional Aviation.  The exercise uses two major regional parks in Seattle, Magnuson Park in northeast Seattle and Discovery Park in Magnolia. It involves the flying and landing of helicopters, and then having the aircraft take off again, fly across town and land at the other park location. The Magnuson Park location is in the grassy area south of the big Sportsfield parking lot. The reason for using Discovery and Magnuson Parks is they are both in the vicinity of emergency shelters and offer large enough areas to accommodate helicopters.
Private meeting, invitation only. Around 50 people anticipated.

events.description:
Nursery Tasks and Plant Sale Preparations
 Volunteer Work Parties are scheduled for April 25 to April 29 and May 2 to May 6 (weekdays) from 10AM to 2PM: come when you can… on arrival, find the Person In Charge (PIC) for an assignment.
 
 Get behind the scenes at Kubota Garden-- come meet others and have fun participating in weeding, raking, watering, moving, trimming, identifying, pricing, labeling, arranging. Don’t forget that your volunteering ahead of the Sale makes you eligible to choose three plants to purchase ahead of the crowds. Sorry, the selection to choose from does not include the blooming plant material nor plants purchased specifically for the Spring Sale.
 
 These work parties are organized to assist the Kubota Garden Foundation (KGF) Nursery. The KGF Nursery Committee takes care of the plants that are sold at the Plant Sales. These Sales are held twice a year (Spring: second Saturday in May—this year May 7 and Fall: the Saturday after Labor Day—this year Sep 10) and help to raise funds to implement the mission of the KGF. (http://www.kubotagarden.org)
 
 The KGF Nursery is located by the Garden Staff Office/headquarters—find us by following the access road south of the main parking lot to the Brown Buildings. Dress in comfortable clothing and wear closed toe shoes. Bring your raingear, this is a Rain or Shine Event!

Attend the Carkeek Park Salmon Stewards 
training and then sign up for three to four, 3-hour 
shifts on Saturdays and Sundays from November 8 
to December 7. Volunteer duties include staffing a 
salmon information table near Piper’s Creek, 
roving Piper’s Creek while engaging visitors, 
answering questions about the salmon return, 
drinking hot cocoa, coffee, tea, keeping tally of 
the location and number of salmon returned, 
and being awesome. Bring your calendar, 
bag lunch, pen, and weather appropriate clothes 
to this great training. School credit is available.

Contact Bill.Malatinsky@Seattle.Gov for more info 
or to sign up. 206-684-5999

 MORE INFO:

Protect Our Waters, in partnership with Seattle 
Public Utilities, is the City of Seattle’s commitment 
to take actions and promote partnerships that protect 
and improve our creeks, lakes, Duwamish River and 
Puget Sound. The Salmon Stewards program forges 
partnership with and trains citizen scientists to thoughtfully 
educate the approximately 3,000 individuals who visit Piper’s 
Creek in Carkeek Park each autumn to view 
the return of spawning chum salmon. By attending 
this training, you'll become a volunteer docent educated 
in best available science. This program allows you to 
communicate effectively on how the adoption of certain 
individual actions can positively affect the health of the 
many waterbodies surrounding Seattle and thus promoting 
the ongoing health of local salmon.
